How Does Accessibility to Commercial Districts Affect the Housing Values? A Case Study in Santa Monica, Los Angeles County

Ta-Yun Yang

Introduction

The factors determining the housing value have been a popular research topic in both academic and business field. These factors can be generalized to three different aspects: Housing Characteristics, Demographic Factors and Geographical Variables. A housing property is more variable if it is newly built and located in decent neighborhood. In this project, the geographical section will be specified and the other elements will be considered as control variables for the housing price evaluation. After controlling demographic and property characteristics, I am particularly interested in the effect of accessibility to commercial services to the property values.

Data and Methods

Commercial districts will be defined as the census blocks which contain the 3 most commercial / industrial properties in the region. The data of the property type can be distinguished in Assessor Parcels Data from Los Angeles County. The parcels data includes more than two million rows for assessed property values and housing characteristics (number of bedrooms, number of bathrooms, building square footage, age) for every tax year. In this project, I plan to analyze the districts around Santa Monica with 3-5 tax year.

With the information of the coordinates in the parcels data, the demographic data from American Community Survey including median income, poverty rate and race can be merged via geojson file of the blocks. ACS dataset contains community information to the unit of Census Block. Finally, instead of calculating the direct distance of properties to the closest commercial district, using average traveling time from Uber Movement Data allows us to include influences from roads, urban planning and landscape. For every commercial district (Census Block), data of traveling time to all the remaining blocks will be collected and merged. The analysis should be done with consideration of the distance to closest commercial district or average distance to multiple districts.

Hypothesis and Discussion

Santa Monica region in Los Angeles County is an appropriate case for the project for several reasons. Firstly, public regional railway system in Greater Los Angeles Area is limited, and automobile remains the most common way for transportation. Thus, the average traveling time of Uber could be a close approximation. Secondly, the heavy industry with pollution which negatively affects the housing price is negligible. On the contrary, the existence of startup tech companies in the region might be positively correlated to the housing price. By concluding the above information, properties are expected to be more valuable if they are closer to commercial districts after demographic and housing patterns are controlled. The main purpose of this project is to test this hypothesis and discover the distribution of the effects.

#@title Default title text
def plot_geo_from_file(center_CT, select_col, col_type, title_dict, legend_title, tooltip_col, center_color="black"):
    '''
    The function take the center census and select columns and
    provide geographical visualization for them
    Inputs:
        center_CT: commercial census tract
        select_cols: columns for visualization
        col_type: the type of the selected columns
    '''
    new_selected = "properties." + select_col + ":Q"
    save_dir = "Data_Viz_proj/data/full_sub_CL" + center_CT + ".geojson"

    with open(save_dir) as f:
        LA_shape_g = json.load(f)
    
    data_geojson = alt.InlineData(values=LA_shape_g, format=alt.DataFormat(property='features',type='json'))

    chart = alt.Chart(data_geojson).mark_geoshape(stroke="black").encode(
                        color=alt.Color(new_selected, type='quantitative', scale=alt.Scale(scheme="yellowgreenblue"), title=legend_title),
                        tooltip=tooltip_col
                        ).properties(
                            width=500,
                            height=400,
                      title=title_dict
    )
    
    label = alt.Chart(geop_file[geop_file["CT"] == 701902]).mark_text(color=center_color, text=["Commercial", "District"]).encode(
                                             latitude="lat",
                                             longitude="lon",
                                             )

    return chart + label

Since the main purpose of the project is to evaluate the relation between the traveling time to commercial district and the property values. First of all, a clear definition of commercial district is necessary for this purpose. The ratio of the building usage type in all regions are presented as the following. We can observe that census tract 701902 (neighborhood) has both high number and proportion of commercial properties. Thus, I define census tract 701902 as commercial district in the following research. Given the fact that region 702300 which contains the most commercial properties are close to tract 701902 (less than 5 min), the commercial districts is concentrated in Santa Monica. Moreover, since the main commercial district of Santa Monica is located along the coast (marked in the map), the traveling time to it is expected to be longer for the inland neighborhoods.

We then take a look into the demographic patterns related to the neighborhoods in Santa Monica. It is a mild trend that in general, neighborhoods with higher median income tend to have higher median property value although this effect is more significant only when the median income is high enough to certain level. On the other hand, there is not clear tendency for the unemployment rate with the property values. Surprisingly, we can clearly see an outlier in this case that the commercial district has relatively low median income and high unemployment rate which are not corresponding to its high median property values.

The above maps demonstrate that the neighborhoods in the sub-urban area tend to have slightly higher property values and median income comparing to the city center. Although the commercial district contains extremely high property values, its local residents are not directly benefited since the high values are attributed to the commercial properties, where the customers and business owner might not live in the region. We are then interested in the factors that drive the property values in the outskirts besides its profitability.

sqft_perc = np.percentile(main_data["SQFTmain"], np.arange(0,100,1))

Out[52]:

Note: House Value labelled in the graph is approximated by the median house value of given neighborhood

  • Source: Los Angeles County Parcels Data, Uber Movement Data, American Community Survey

There exist possibilities that the value of a residential property is driven by its own housing characteristics beside all factors in the community. A clear linear pattern between square footage of a residential building and its value can be observed since higher square footage of a building could result in higher living qualities. Furthermore, they are both positively correlated with the traveling time to the main commercial district. This provides us an explanation that the high value of the properties in the sub-urban regions might be attributed to the value of higher living qualities. In contrast, we do not observe the similar clear pattern in commercial properties although properties with extremely large square footage are still more valuable. The value of the commercial properties is more likely to be related to its profitability and locations.

#@title Default title text
def create_yearly_table(grouped_data, selected_columns, year_list,
                        group_col="CT", group_thres=np.arange(0,1,0.2)):
    '''
    The function take the summarized table with the selected columns and year list
    and provide information of the time trend for different sub-group specified in
    group_col parameter
    Inputs:
        grouped_data: summarized table for census tracts
        selected_columns: columns to be kept in the final table
        year_list: The tax year for House Value included
        group_col: columns for creating sub-groups
        group_thres: percentile taken to group the group_col
    Return: summarized table grouped by group_col and year
    '''
    final_df = grouped_data[selected_columns]
    final_df["year"] = 2018
    if group_col != "CT":
        for i, thres in enumerate(group_thres):
            final_df.loc[final_df[group_col] >= final_df[group_col].quantile(
                         thres), group_col + "_b"] = i * 20
    
    for year in year_list:
        temp = grouped_data
        valcol = "TotalValue" + str(year)
        temp["TotalValue"] = temp[valcol]
        temp = temp[selected_columns]
        temp["year"] = year
        if group_col != "CT":
            for i, thres in enumerate(group_thres):
                temp.loc[temp[group_col] >= temp[group_col].quantile(
                         thres), group_col + "_b"] = i * 20
            
        final_df = pd.concat([final_df, temp], join="inner")
    
    return final_df

  • Data Source: Los Angeles County Parcels Data, Uber Movement Data, American Community Survey

Finally, we are interested in the property values over time. The distribution of median property values in communities is varying toward the right which demonstrates a fact that the property values are increasing in general. The main force of the growth in property values come from the middle and high valued properties. On the contrary, the value of the low-valued properties remains over time. The inequality in the value growth might be driven by several kinds of patterns which require further studies. According to our analysis above, the increase might be driven by the boom in commercial or industrial housing market which are less effective to the residential properties in the neighborhoods.

Conclusion

Overall, our analysis can be summarized to several points

  • Commercial and Industrial properties are significantly more valuable than the residential properties due to their profitability
  • The values of commercial properties are driven by their distances to the main commercial district or the main roads
  • The value of residential properties is strongly related to their housing characteristics and slightly related to the environments of the neighborhoods
  • Residential properties in sub-urban neighborhoods in Santa Monica are characterized with higher median income and property values comparing to the main commercial district (city center)
  • The growth in property values are concentrated in the middle and high-valued properties which results in the increase of inequality
